Cell.Data: VSOS Standards Model Summary for C / C++
The LDRA tool suite® is developed and certified to BS EN ISO 9001:2000.
This information is applicable to version 9.4.4 of the LDRA tool suite®. It is correct as of 25th April 2014.

Cell.Data: VSOS Standards Model Compliance for C / C++
Procedure has more than one exit point.
Function does not return a value on all paths.
No declaration for variable found before use.
Procedure definition has no associated prototype.
Scope of variable could be reduced.
Variable should be defined once in only one file.
No real declaration for external variable.
Procedure name re-used in different files.
More than one control variable for loop.
Procedure call has no prototype declared.
Local pointer returned in function result.
UR anomaly, variable used before assignment.
Named variable declared but not used in code.
Call has execution order dependant side effects.
More than *** executable reformatted lines in file.
No brackets to loop body (added by Testbed).
No brackets to then/else (added by Testbed).
Procedural para used in an uncalled procedure.
Number of parameters does not match.
Use of obsolete language feature ( use = - ).
Loop control expression may not terminate loop.
Deprecated usage of ++ or -- operators found.
Use of break statement in loop.
Procedure parameter has a type but no identifier.
Ellipsis used in procedure parameter list.
Use of banned function or variable.
extern not in nominated include file.
No default case in switch statement.
Use of shift operator on signed type.
Expression with more than one function.
Switch case not terminated with break.
Signed bit field less than 2 bits wide.
Bit field not signed or unsigned int.
Executable code before an included file.
More than one of # or ## in a macro.
char type not signed or unsigned.
Name redeclared in another C name space (MR).
Duplicate use of a name in an enumeration.
Value is not of appropriate type.
Function use is not a call.
Label is not part of switch statement (MR).
Use of bit operator on signed type.
Use of boolean expression in switch.
Use of ## or # in a macro.
Parameter has same name as global variable.
Parameter has same name as type or tag.
Assignment operator in RHS of && or ||.
Anonymous bit field used in structure.
Procedure call has no prototype and no defn.
Non standard escape sequence in source.
Identifier not declared on new line.
Declaration statement not on new line.
{ or } not on line by itself.
Use of numeric literal in expression.
Macro name is not upper case.
Pointer name does not have required suffix.
Operation not appropriate to plain char.
Literal value requires a U suffix.
Use of ++ or -- on RHS of && or || operator.
Volatile variable accessed on RHS of && or ||.
Use of // comment in pre-processor directive or macro defn.
Declaration types do not match across a system.
